                <td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=26625&amp;sid=d9798aa9cf04a8c87888835d37842656#26625"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Mon Feb 23, 2004 3:26 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=26625&amp;sid=d9798aa9cf04a8c87888835d37842656"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">CC starts with the pulling. Bards are better at pulling, if only because of fading memory.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   There are a variety of reasons for this, but it is fair to say Bards have a better set of abilities for pulling.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Let's look at mezzing. Bard songs do not have a recast time. This means that a bard does not have to wait 2.2 seconds in case of a resist, or to mez another mob after retargetting.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   However, Bard mez has a longer actual casting time.  In addition, Bard mez is not only resisted more often upfront, but Bards don't possess a quick-casting long duration MR debuff.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Their songs also generate minimal aggro, which is usually a huge advantage, and if they do they can either stand there and take hits a lot more easily than an enchanter due to their vastly superior defensive skills, or they can simply run around since they can cast on the run.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   Unfortunately, <span style="font-weight: bold">because</span> Bard mez has virtually no aggro component to it, they can't actually 'kite' the mob anywhere near their group- they won't hold aggro and the mob will start hitting groupmates.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Bards also can't be interrupted unless stunned (no channeling checks).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   Of course, Enchanters can't even be stunned if they have a Rune up.  Since the 'anti-kiting' code makes bash-on-arrival a near-guaranteed interrupt, this is a massive advantage possessed by Enchanters over Bards.  While the Rune won't hold up for long, it will hold up for that first crucial blow that would auto-interrupt the Bard.
<br />

<br />
   In addition, almost every CC spell possessed by Enchanters casts either slightly or significantly faster than any Bard song.  The faster the casting time, the less chance of being interrupted.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">With 3 and less mobs to mez, bards can do it faster, indefinitely (no mana used)</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   Mesmerize is a cheap enough and long enough duration spell that with 1-2 mobs (depending on the mana regeneration available), an Enchanter can keep 2 mobs mesmerized indefinitely as well.  In addition, when an Enchanter mesmerizes 2+ mobs, your group doesn't suddenly start to lose its haste and mana regeneration.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">and a lot more safely (resists are largely irrelevant to them).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   They have less relevance only in that a resisted mez doesn't guarantee aggro on a cloth caster.  However, it does mean 3 more seconds of a mob running around loose striking at groupmates.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It's a cheap solution and would trivialize a lot of content, but I haven't been able to come up with outstanding ideas.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   It remains to be seen that there is actually a <span style="font-weight: bold">problem</span>.  In virtually any situation where both a Bard and an Enchanter are present, the Enchanter handles the primary responsibility for crowd control.  This should give some indication that your assessment of 'Bards are better at CC' isn't really accurate.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
	<tr>
