                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">However, Bard mez has a longer actual casting time. In addition, Bard mez is not only resisted more often upfront, but Bards don't possess a quick-casting long duration MR debuff. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Consider this though, bards can oos first on resistant mobs without getting any aggro - you can't do that with tash.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Unfortunately, because Bard mez has virtually no aggro component to it, they can't actually 'kite' the mob anywhere near their group- they won't hold aggro and the mob will start hitting groupmates. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Right. What I was saying though is, bards get a lot less aggro *AND* are much better at mitigating it.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Of course, Enchanters can't even be stunned if they have a Rune up.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Wrong. Runes will prevent pushback effects and innate procs, but don't do anything for bashes and stuns. What's more, this small advantage of arcane rune can't be one compared to a class that probably won't get aggro to start with, and doesn't have to stand and take the hits if they do.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">They have less relevance only in that a resisted mez doesn't guarantee aggro on a cloth caster. However, it does mean 3 more seconds of a mob running around loose striking at groupmates. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Except that if the enchanter does get resisted, it will probably mean aggro on a robed caster anyway i.e. the enchanter himself. 
<br />

<br />
I can agree that there are instances where the enchanter getting aggro from a resist can be a good thing, but in general, it's not the case.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Mesmerize is a cheap enough and long enough duration spell that with 1-2 mobs (depending on the mana regeneration available), an Enchanter can keep 2 mobs mesmerized indefinitely as well. In addition, when an Enchanter mesmerizes 2+ mobs, your group doesn't suddenly start to lose its haste and mana regeneration. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
Indeed the limitations that bards have regarding the effects they can keep up at the same time are very real in groups. However, the other effects that an enchanter could keep going while mezzing - slow/haste/mana regen aren't a factor at all in raids - your VoQ and vallons aren't going to drop if the bard is mezzing. What I mean is that yes, the bardic advantage at crowd control won't necessarily mean that they are superior in groups. But they certainly are overwhelmingly stronger in raids where the bardic limitations on number of effects being up at once don't mean that much.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In virtually any situation where both a Bard and an Enchanter are present, the Enchanter handles the primary responsibility for crowd control. This should give some indication that your assessment of 'Bards are better at CC' isn't really accurate.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Not necessarily. It's just like in early pop when groups were letting the warrior tank if the group happened to have both a knight and a warrior, or the monk pull if you have a bard, etc... It's going to take a bit to change perceptions and habits.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
