                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Consider this though, bards can oos first on resistant mobs without getting any aggro - you can't do that with tash.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   Again, you're failing to realize that while a no-aggro Tash would be an advantage for an Enchanter, it works out to being a <span style="font-weight: bold">disadvantage</span> for Bards.  If Harmony of Sound generated Tash-like aggro, it would make the Bard's life much easier, since he could simply off-tank the add while he mezzed it, rather than having to mez the mob off the cleric or a cloth claster.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Indeed the limitations that bards have regarding the effects they can keep up at the same time are very real in groups. However, the other effects that an enchanter could keep going while mezzing - slow/haste/mana regen aren't a factor at all in raids - your VoQ and vallons aren't going to drop if the bard is mezzing.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   But the stackable buffs the Bard is playing will drop.  Indeed, the presence of Vallon's means that one song a Bard might potentially play (Warsong of Zek) is reduced in value- it still provides a significant damage shield and attack buff.  The presence of VoQ means nothing, since you still get full effect from Marr.
<br />

<br />
   In general, the only time you see Bards having primary responsibility for crowd control on raids is either in very specific circumstances (10th Ring War, for example) or when you don't have enough Enchanters.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Not necessarily. It's just like in early pop when groups were letting the warrior tank if the group happened to have both a knight and a warrior, or the monk pull if you have a bard, etc... It's going to take a bit to change perceptions and habits.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   I don't think these perceptions and habits will change- because there are solid game mechanics behind them.  When you have the Enchanter running crowd control, the risk is greater to the Enchanter.  When you have the Bard running crowd control, the risk is greater to the group/raid.  It should be rather obvious which element of risk is more acceptable.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
