                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">While healing is inarguably a more universal feature of raids than crowd control, essentially all of your arguments can be used to justify the position "Paladins are better healers than Clerics". I pointed this out to showcase how weak those arguments were. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I could agree with that if I would agree that bards are superior at crowd control only because of superior melee mitigation, but that's not the case.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Enchanters: Mesmerize, Charm, Root, Memory Blur, Stun, Pacify 
<br />
Bards: Mesmerize, Highsun, Pacify </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Charm as a general rule isn't a crowd control method. What can be charmed, with very few exceptions like Kael giants, can be mezzed as well. 
<br />

<br />
Among bard options, you neglected the ability to cast on the run, or fading memories to do crowd control out of camp in the first place - which is what GoD is about.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Harmony of Sound takes 3 seconds to cast, and lasts 3 ticks. As a result, the situation you're trying to argue makes Bards 'better' essentially never occurs. You simply don't waste 3 seconds with a mob running around in camp to debuff resists first. You try a mez; and if that doesn't work, you try a mez again. The chance of both the mezzes failing almost always counterbalances the certainty of not locking the mob down for 6+ seconds while you Harmony of Sound first. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I am gonna have to disagree with that. On certain mobs, I *have* to tash first because I know mez is very likely to bounce. In the situations where you have to tash or oos first, I can't believe you won't agree that bards have a huge advantage there, as the enchanter will draw aggro. and the bard won't. Plus, you will mez faster by 0.3 sec as the enchanter (1.0 (tash), 2.2 (spell recovery), 2.5 (mez) ), which is very little. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Recovery time occurs after you've cast a spell, so I'm not sure why you're arguing that it's part of 'casting time'. It obviously isn't. Now, arguably the 'cyclic rate' of Bard mesmerize is faster, but Enchanters don't have to chain-mez mobs like Bards do. They just have to mez it once every 45 seconds or so. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
What's really important about crowd control is the initial lock down. Once it's locked down, the important part is done. Yes it's easier for an enchanter from that point on, but you should be out of the danger zone. If you have a single add to mez, the enchanter can mez it potentially faster by 0.5 seconds. If you have 2, a bard can lock them down in 6.0 sec, and an enchanter will need 7.2. If you have 3, a bard can lock them in 9.0, and an enchanter will need 11.9.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">With 2 or more secondary mobs, an Enchanter can control them without losing any of his effectiveness towards the group. With 2 or more secondary mobs, a Bard loses essentially all of his direct DPS and the group starts losing the Bard's indirect DPS via their buffs dropping. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I agree. But we're talking about crowd control here. This is why I mentioned earlier that because of bardic limitations on the number of effects they can keep going at the same time, bards aren't necessarily always an obviously better choice in groups. But they certainly are in raids, because you won't lose anything by replacing an enchanter by a bard, but you'll certainly gain a lot - that is as long as you still have at least one enchanter buff-bot.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Are you claiming the game is so trivialized that we never see 3-mob fights any more? Because I see them all the time.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The overwhelming majority of pulls in GoD or pop in single groups are 3 mobs or less, which means enchanters won't have a crowd control advantage. 4+ is a rare event, and it's very hard to survive the massive dps of the initial shock anyway. With this size of pull, crowd control needs to be done out of camp - see bards for this.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">There is no comparison here. Enchanters get explicit aggro reduction methods. Bards get zero aggro enhancement methods. It's like claiming that both Druid nukes and Rogue healing aren't very good. Well, this is true, but it's a silly comparison. The marginal value of Druid nukes is vastly greater than the nonexistant value of Rogue healing. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Fine, I am all for drastically increasing bardic aggro on songs then. Or massively reduce aggro on enchanter spells. It seems it's both something we agree that should be corrected.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Many times it's better to do CC out of camp. But sometimes it isn't, and many times it can't be. And when those mobs are in camp, who do you get to control them? An Enchanter. 
<br />

<br />
I could just as easily argue that kiting is a superior form of fighting to tanking. When you're kiting, you essentially swap out two non-DPS group slots (tank, healer) for two DPS group slots, so you can kill much faster. But you can't always kite. The fact that a Druid can run around chain-snaring a non-summoning mob to keep it from hitting anyone doesn't change the fact that a Warrior is a far better tank than a D</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
No you can't because you're not doing a valid comparison. It's usually better to do crowd control out of camp. If it's not possible, then there can be situations where using an enchanter is better, but in the general sense of crowd control, it's usually better done out of camp - see bards for that.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
