                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Charm as a general rule isn't a crowd control method. What can be charmed, with very few exceptions like Kael giants, can be mezzed as well.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   Charm lasts longer and can be used to subtract two mobs from the fight rather than just one.  Indeed, except for the recent aberration of using perma-charmed pets as DPS, charm has always been a crowd control method.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Among bard options, you neglected the ability to cast on the run, or fading memories to do crowd control out of camp in the first place - which is what GoD is about.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   Because 'casting on the run' isn't an 'option'- if a mob is unmezzable, it's unmezzable whether or not you're moving when you cast the mez, and pulling isn't what we're discussing.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I am gonna have to disagree with that. On certain mobs, I *have* to tash first because I know mez is very likely to bounce. In the situations where you have to tash or oos first, I can't believe you won't agree that bards have a huge advantage there, as the enchanter will draw aggro. and the bard won't. Plus, you will mez faster by 0.3 sec as the enchanter (1.0 (tash), 2.2 (spell recovery), 2.5 (mez) ), which is very little.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   The Bard is actually slower by 0.3 sec (1.0 + 2.2 + 2.5 = 5.7; 3.0 + 3.0 = 6.0).  And you're explaining a situation where the Bard is dramatically inferior to the Enchanter in actual play.  The Enchanter Tash's and mezzes- and then leaves the mob alone for the next 40 seconds.  The Bard uses HoS and mezzes- and then has to repeat the process 6 seconds later, consuming half of his total song complement.  Moreover, this situation occurs more for Bards than Enchanters, since Enchanters have intrinsically lower resists on their mesmerize.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">What's really important about crowd control is the initial lock down. Once it's locked down, the important part is done. Yes it's easier for an enchanter from that point on, but you should be out of the danger zone. If you have a single add to mez, the enchanter can mez it potentially faster by 0.5 seconds. If you have 2, a bard can lock them down in 6.0 sec, and an enchanter will need 7.2. If you have 3, a bard can lock them in 9.0, and an enchanter will need 11.9.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   And, of course, the penalty for having the Bard doing the lockdown rises as you increase the number of mobs.  So the fact that the Bard can theoretically lock down 10 mobs faster than an Enchanter can is nicely counterbalanced by the fact that you just took your Bard completely out of the fight- and he can't lock down that many mobs anyway.
<br />

<br />
   You're also forgetting about Word of Morell, which an Enchanter can use to instantly stop an arbitrary large number of mobs for a brief period of time.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">But they certainly are in raids, because you won't lose anything by replacing an enchanter by a bard, but you'll certainly gain a lot - that is as long as you still have at least one enchanter buff-bot.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   If you were to do this, you'd probably have to bring 3-4 Bards per Enchanter you replaced.  And you couldn't do it at all on certain raids.  Again, you're straying into "Paladins are better than Clerics" territory.  Especially on raids, you don't want Bards doing CC because the mobs you're mesmerizing tend to be higher level- and have resist issues.  When you couple the higher resist on Bard mez with the need for repeated casting, you get a rather dramatic difference in overall resist rates.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The overwhelming majority of pulls in GoD or pop in single groups are 3 mobs or less, which means enchanters won't have a crowd control advantage.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   And, at 3 mobs, the Enchanter enjoys a substantial advantage.  Crowd Control has never been an 'every fight' necessity- you bring Crowd Control for the occaisional fight in which you need it.  And you don't need a large pull for CC to become necessary- wanderers can path into camp unexpectedly.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">No you can't because you're not doing a valid comparison. It's usually better to do crowd control out of camp.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   Why is it not a valid comparison?  Name one fight where kiting is a reasonable option and it's preferable to tank the mob rather than kite it.  The simple fact is that there are many fights where you can't kite- not enough room, summoning mobs, etc.- and are forced to use the tank + healer method.  And there are many fights where it is essentially impossible to split pull- especially on raids.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If it's not possible, then there can be situations where using an enchanter is better, but in the general sense of crowd control, it's usually better done out of camp - see bards for that.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
   So Monks, Necromancers and Shadowknights are superior CC classes to Enchanters as well?</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
